description:
File: rust/lichen-schc/src/fragment.rs
Lines: 486-493 (abs_window function)

Category: PROTOCOL

The FragmentReceiver::abs_window() method maps the 1-bit wire window to an absolute window number using only the current_window state:
```rust
fn abs_window(&self, frag: &Fragment<'_>) -> usize {
    if frag.window == (self.current_window % 2) as u8 {
        self.current_window
    } else {
        self.current_window + 1
    }
}
```

This assumes fragments only arrive from window N or N+1. If a sender misbehaves or network conditions cause fragments from window N+2 to arrive, they would be misinterpreted as window N (both have the same wire bit).

Example: current_window=2, fragment from window 4 (wire bit=0) -> mapped to window 2 instead of 4.

Impact: Protocol violation or buggy sender could cause incorrect reassembly and data corruption.

Note: RFC 8724 ACK-on-Error mode uses 1-bit window field, which inherently cannot distinguish N from N+2. The receiver relies on the sender to not advance more than one window without ACK. Adding explicit detection/rejection of out-of-sequence windows would improve robustness.
